posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Do you have a GripPipeline class defined?  The third parameter here is actually a function that accepts pipeline as a parameter.  The code inside that function is calling back into the GripPipeline class (e.g. pipeline.filterContoursOutput() ) so the GripPipeline class would need to have those functions defined.

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: yes, I just put a random letter in front of “pipeline” and it seemed to recognize it, do you know what I am supposed to put in front of the 3rd parameter? It wants me to claim the pipeline’s “type”

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: The Java syntax there is correct.  If you don’t have a GripPipeline class, the new GripPipeline() part of the code won’t work, so it can’t figure out the type of the third parameter (which depends on the type of the second parameter).

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: oh I looked through my GripPipeline class that grip made for me and there is no filtercontours subclass so maybe I just need to make my own code and not use the frc’s example.

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: Nope, still doesn’t work. It says “the constructor VisionThread(Camera, GripPipeline, ( pipeline) → {}) is undefinedJava(134217858)”

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Oh.  Just looking higher in your code… what is Camera in your code?  If you look at the WPILib example, it does UsbCamera camera = CameraServer.startAutomaticCapture();

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: When I do “import edu.wpi.cscore.UsbCamera;” java cant find it

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: It was renamed in 2022.  It’s now edu.wpi.first.cscore.UsbCamera .

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: however i have a Camera.java file that sets the resolution and starts automatic capture with its constructor

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: The VisionThread constructor first parameter must be based on edu.wpi.first.cscore.VideoSource .

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: I just changed the camera instantiation to that, but still have the same error. I cant send you my grippipeline program because im a new user. Ill try to do it through google drive.

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1B3hejSC51i_drFjKrjkW85kCH4hY7M1I?usp=sharing

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: you shouldn’t have the “P”, it should just be: visionThread = new VisionThread(camera, new GripPipeline(), pipeline -> {});

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: Even when I do that, I get the same error with the constructor.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Oh, your GripPipeline needs to implement the VisionPipeline interface (e.g. public class GripPipeline implements VisionPipeline ).

posts.name: Henry
posts.cooked: WOw thats like white on rice we almost threw in the towel, now slap me silly annd call me sally, it worked! Really appreciate it man!

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: That error would be due to your GripPipeline not having that processing stage or function.  You should customize that part to match what image processing steps you’re actually doing.

posts.name: Caden Feller
posts.cooked: Ah, ok. How do you think would be the best way do go about doing that?
